<div id="review_2454364148" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2454364148" />
    <a title="Joey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10049704-joey"><img alt="Joey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609511275p2/10049704.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2454364148?book_show_action=true">Jul 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joey" href="/user/show/10049704-joey">Joey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10049704-joey?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2454364148" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7664500224285750329">I was like one of those members of the audience in a grand opera house, riveted on the presence of a passionate narrator, carried away by each and every line that went deeper into my heart until it displayed vivid imagination. I would disregard the background and backup actors illustrating the settings, plots, and dialogues. Rather, the deep, emotional, narrative, and lyrical execution of the narrator was enough to hold me in fascination. When the show ended, I would still sit into my armchair m</span>
  <span id="freeText7664500224285750329" style="display:none">I was like one of those members of the audience in a grand opera house, riveted on the presence of a passionate narrator, carried away by each and every line that went deeper into my heart until it displayed vivid imagination. I would disregard the background and backup actors illustrating the settings, plots, and dialogues. Rather, the deep, emotional, narrative, and lyrical execution of the narrator was enough to hold me in fascination. When the show ended, I would still sit into my armchair musing over the lines that had just had an impact on me and wait for its second showing for the next batch who may have missed it. But alas, I would be short of time because there were more plays I had to keep up with. Gee, fie on me, this is how I would figuratively feel when I read other E. L Doctorow’s novels regardless of their themes – war, gangster, romance, crime and so on.<br /><br />Billy Bathgate, since I have read two of E.L. Doctorow’s works, has supported my literary observation that the author himself appears to have the penchant for writing a novel riddled with lyrical narratives rather than writing one with conversational contents. His writing style is kind of similar to Marilyne Robinson. ( Lila is one of her finest works for me.) Besides, it attests to the fact that E.L Doctorow was a genius writer, and no wonder he was considered by former US President Barack Obama as one of America’s greatest contemporary writers; he had exceptional skills in giving life to his novels steeped in American social issues.That’s why an Asian reader like me tends to engross myself in them.<br /><br />The concept of the story is not new to me. I have watched its scenarios in movies several times. I could even predict the climax and ending in that I wanted to put it aside for a short while and look through the other book I could find gripping. I even shrank back when I learned that it bears little resemblance to The Adventures of Tom Sawyer. However, I swallowed my words when I found the elements that comprise the whole story perfectly rhetorical. First, Billy Bathgate is the narrator himself. He is like a poor teenager telling us about his abject miseries , living in a squalid house in a huge city with his schizophrenic mother, abandoned by his Jewish father. The climax of his story is how he will become the protégé and surrogate son of the notorious mobster,Dutch Schultz. Unlike Huckleberry Finn’s characterization of a bold, rustic adventurer, Billy Bathgate’s characterization of being a brave but meek boy with a pure heart adds deeper and more oozing emotions to the whole story. I can feel Billy’s hidden desire to have a father figure who can take care of him, his unconditional love for his mother, and his remarkable resiliency impermeable to social and moral evils. Second, the secret love affair between his surrogate father’s kept-woman and him, a part of the story I have rarely seen in movies . Third, all the vivid descriptions of the old New York City as a metropolis play a huge picture in my imagination. And the image of that city does not even expiate right from the start of the story to the ending. As a result of all the literary elements above, the narratives become exquisitely complementary.<br /><br />Because of this novel, I want to point out more that E. L Doctorow is one of my favorite writers although it is now my third work of his. Without clearer reasons, I would always feel like making his work one of my priorities to read. I can even predict, in fact, that when I come to the point of running out of books to read, or when I reach the senescent stage of my life, his books would be one of those books I would be absorbed in at a coffee shop. 🙂</span>
  <a data-text-id="7664500224285750329" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


