    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_510941511" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/510941511" />
    <a title="Deb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5276322-deb"><img alt="Deb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526245087p2/5276322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/510941511?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deb" href="/user/show/5276322-deb">Deb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394525297" href="/book/show/1100097.Billy_Bathgate">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer510941511" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9086412957781648037">This wasn&apos;t exactly what I expected it to be but I&apos;m so glad it was a winner within it&apos;s own right. I really enjoyed it. E.L. Doctorow is a new author to me whom I discovered on a whim while searching for new books here on Goodreads. From the synopsis I assumed it might be more thriller/action packed and even when it wasn&apos;t so much so, it still was a very good read for what it did bring to the table. <br/><br/>This is the story of a young man self christened Billy Bathgate, local neighborhood kid slash as</span>
  <span id="freeText9086412957781648037" style="display:none">This wasn't exactly what I expected it to be but I'm so glad it was a winner within it's own right. I really enjoyed it. E.L. Doctorow is a new author to me whom I discovered on a whim while searching for new books here on Goodreads. From the synopsis I assumed it might be more thriller/action packed and even when it wasn't so much so, it still was a very good read for what it did bring to the table. <br /><br />This is the story of a young man self christened Billy Bathgate, local neighborhood kid slash aspiring gangster circa early 1930's. Billy asserts himself and kind of accidently wiggles his way into the Dutch Schultz mob, a gang famous for it's gambling, racketeering, murdering as well as various other undercover activities. Billy shadows the gang for the same reason any boy wants to join a gang, for the comradery and attention not found at home, the attraction of more money, the power and to move above his current station. Where Billy was just another ordinary kid from around the corner in the neighborhood, taken under the wing of the gang, he learns he can be useful to it's members. This is the tale of 15 year old Billy Bathgate, what he sees, what he learns, how it changes him and he can never go back.<br /><br />However, this book is not just about Billy's experience with the inner workings of the gang and their "business". This is also a story of parallel discovery. On the surface there is the story of what is currently happening with the Dutch Schultz mob and their troubles around the time that Billy enters the picture. Below ground there is the connection between Billy and the gang. Everything that Billy is missing in his personal home life, he finds a little something within each member of the gang. As the gang metamorphosizes into something new, so does Billy. The beginning of the end of the beginning. <br /><br />I liked the way the author was very vivid in his description but not overly. Everything fit and also a story was told. I liked how it was written so that you could almost hear the voices, the very accents of these people. I was continuously interested. I will read other books by this author and would actually read this book over again, which is a rare statement from me. <br />At times, yes I was on the edge of my seat. Dealing with gangsters, you never know when someone may fly off the handle. I do recommend this to historical fiction readers and people who like when characters narrate the story. It was very entertaining and easy to read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9086412957781648037" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


