<div id="review_2322513399" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2322513399" />
    <a title="Pickle." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17340505-pickle"><img alt="Pickle." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534409945p2/17340505.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2322513399?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pickle." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pickle." href="/user/show/17340505-pickle">Pickle.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=crime">crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17340505-pickle?shelf=20th-c-classics">20th-c-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2322513399" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5700687682170600268">4.5* <br/><br/>I can’t really add much to what has already been said about this rather excellent historical fiction of figures from the 30’s NYC underworld, but some parts which particularly stood out warrant mentioning:<br/><br/>Some of the best writing is in describing the blossoming covert relationship between Billy and Drew , (Boss ‘Dutch’ Schultz’s ‘moll’) the added excitement of real danger and tragedy, the metaphoric vein throughout of the young juggler struggling to keep all of the morbidly risky relationsh</span>
  <span id="freeText5700687682170600268" style="display:none">4.5* <br /><br />I can’t really add much to what has already been said about this rather excellent historical fiction of figures from the 30’s NYC underworld, but some parts which particularly stood out warrant mentioning:<br /><br />Some of the best writing is in describing the blossoming covert relationship between Billy and Drew , (Boss ‘Dutch’ Schultz’s ‘moll’) the added excitement of real danger and tragedy, the metaphoric vein throughout of the young juggler struggling to keep all of the morbidly risky relationships and dealings aloft.<br />A recognisable young love- small touches of painful jealousies (even once of a handsome horse averting Drew’s gaze!) and subsequent relief, beautifully heartfelt in first person. Highly cinematic set pieces such as the conspiratorial rushing back to their adjoining rooms entering each adjacent door to fool spying eyes and giggling rush inside to meet between, are on a par with the Carlito and Gail latched door scene, (‘Carlito’s Way’), Noodles watching Deborah dance (‘Once upon a time in America’).<br /><br />Another incredible scene is a certain post-murder clean up and alibi setting, more wince inducing than any of the most violent scenes.... palpable surrounding menace in sharp broad shouldered suits - I’m not sure I’ve ever said ‘no.....what are you doing!’ to a book before.<br /><br />Billys narrative voice ‘grows’ with his experience, the articulation of his feelings becomes more sophisticated and nuanced along the way, this adds to the sadness of his reflections, when he returns home especially, latterly his voice becomes tinged with a nostalgia. <br /><br />I think I’ll give the film version a miss judging by the reviews, surely a missed opportunity? I mean the masses of flowers sent by Billy to surround Drew with the horse racing crowds attention - safety from a perceived oncoming hit - crying out for stunning depiction in a good directors hands.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5700687682170600268" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


